\begin_layout Subsection
Slope in DEM
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For each cell, Slope calculates the maximum rate of change in value from
 that cell to its neighbors.
 Basically, the maximum change in elevation over the distance between the
 cell and its eight neighbors identifies the steepest downhill descent from
 the cell.
 Conceptually, the Slope function fits a plane to the z-values of a 3 x
 3 cell neighborhood around the processing or centered cell.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The rate of change in the x direction for cell 'e' is calculated with the
 algorithm: The neighbors are identified as letters from 'a' to 'i', with
 'e' representing the cell for which the aspect is being calculated.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
placement H
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename 11.gif

\end_inset


\begin_inset Caption

\begin_layout Plain Layout
3x3 window of cells
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
[dz/dx=((c+2f+i)-(a+2d+g)/(8*x_{cellsize})]
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The rate of change in the y direction for cell 'e' is calculated with the
 following algorithm:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
[dz/dy=((g+2h+i)-(a+2b+c)/(8*y_{cellsize})]
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

